8 PROPOSED POLICY COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
9 An Act relating to education; defining terms;
authorizing the State Regents for Higher Education
10 and the Department of Career and Technology Education
to designate a credential of value; listing criteria
11 for a credential of value; permitting the designation
of a credential of value if the credential is
12 determined to be essential to meeting documented
state workforce needs; authorizing the State Regents
13 and the Department to adopt a definition of self-
sufficient wage; authorizing the State Regents and
14 the Department to promulgate rules and determine
procedures to implement the section; requiring annual
15 report from institutions, agencies, and schools on
data required to evaluate credentials under this
16 section; requiring the State Regents and the
Department to annually publish a statewide credential
17 of value list; authorizing the State Regents and the
Department to enter into data-sharing agreements; and
18 providing for codification.
19
20 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
21 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 9201 of Title 70, unless there
23 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24 A. As used in this section:
Req. No. 16132 Page 1

1 1. "Coordinating entity" means the Oklahoma State Regents for
2 Higher Education or the Oklahoma Department of Career and Technology
3 Education;
4 2. "Credential of value" means a certificate, degree, license,
5 industry-recognized credential, apprenticeship credential, or other
6 postsecondary or career-technical award issued by an educational
7 provider that meets the criteria established under this section;
8 3. "Educational provider" means any institution, agency, or
9 school coordinated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
10 Education or governed by the Oklahoma Department of Career and
11 Technology Education; and
12 4. "Net cost of attendance" means the cost of attendance minus
13 all grants, scholarships, fee waivers, or other aid received by the
14 individual.
15 B. A coordinating entity may designate a credential as a
16 credential of value if the credential satisfies the following
17 criteria:
18 1. The credential provides a positive return on investment for
19 individuals who complete the credential, demonstrated by:
20 a. cumulative earnings within a time period specified by
21 the coordinating entity that coordinates or governs
22 the educational provider that are equal to or exceed
23 the statewide median earnings for Oklahoma high school
24 graduates, and
Req. No. 16132 Page 2

1 b. earnings that allow the credential holder to recoup
2 the net cost of attendance within a time period
3 specified by the coordinating entity that coordinates
4 or governs the educational provider; and
5 2. The credential is aligned with state and regional labor
6 market demand, as determined by the coordinating entity that
7 coordinates or governs the educational provider, using data from the
8 Oklahoma Employment Security Commission, the Oklahoma Workforce
9 Commission, or other labor market sources recognized by the
10 coordinating entity.
11 C. A coordinating entity may designate a credential as a
12 credential of value even if it does not meet one or more criteria
13 under subsection B of this section if the credential is determined
14 by the coordinating entity to be essential to meeting documented
15 state workforce needs.
16 D. A coordinating entity may adopt a definition of a self-
17 sufficient wage for purposes of this section that aligns with:
18 1. Statewide self-sufficiency wage benchmarks; or
19 2. Regional economic and labor market data that reflect the
20 cost of living and labor market conditions in Oklahoma.
21 E. A coordinating entity may promulgate rules and determine
22 procedures to implement the provisions of this section, including:
23 1. Standard methodologies for calculating return on investment
24 and net cost of attendance;
Req. No. 16132 Page 3

1 2. Criteria and data sources for assessing alignment with
2 workforce demand;
3 3. A unified statewide process for designating and periodically
4 reviewing credentials of value; and
5 4. A shared reporting structure and timeline for all education
6 providers under the coordination or governance of the coordinating
7 entity.
8 F. 1. Each educational provider shall annually report the data
9 required to evaluate credentials under this section to the
10 coordinating entity that coordinates or governs the educational
11 provider. Such data shall include, but is not limited to, the
12 following:
13 a. enrollment, completion, and credential attainment,
14 b. graduate employment rate and earnings outcomes, and
15 c. program cost information.
16 2. A coordinating entity shall annually publish a statewide
17 credential of value list, accessible to the public, identifying all
18 credentials designated under this section.
19 G. A coordinating entity may enter into data-sharing agreements
20 with the Oklahoma Employment Security Commission, the Oklahoma
21 Workforce Commission, and other state agencies to support the
22 evaluation and designation of credentials of value.
